{"type":"message","id":"b4ce42bf","parentId":"84021f23","timestamp":"2026-05-15T03:57:15.994Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, the process exited with SIGKILL (signal 9). That means the bat process was killed. Let me check - did I kill it? Or was it the bat that killed its own child process?\n\nActually, the `-quit` flag in Unity causes Unity to exit, and when the child Unity process exits, the bat process continues on and exits normally. But SIGKILL means it was killed externally.\n\nLet me check the bat session one more time - maybe the log was just showing stdio. Actually, looking at the bat script:\n\n```\n\"%UNITY_PATH%\" -batchmode -quit -nographics -projectPath \"%PROJECT_PATH%\" -executeMethod YYZY.BuildPipeline.BuildPipeline.RunHotUpdatePipeline -logFile \"%LOG_FILE%\"\n\necho [INFO] Unity 退出码: %ERRORLEVEL%\nexit /b %ERRORLEVEL%\n```\n\nThe bat first runs Unity (which exits on its own because of -quit), then prints the exit code. But the SIGKILL was sent to the whole bat process.\n\nWait, I see the process was already running and I used `background: true`. Let me check if the first run's process (session `brisk-harbor`) was still lingering.\n\nActually, looking at the poll result, it shows the stdout from the bat (the echo lines at the top), but doesn't show \"Unity 退出码:\". This means Unity was still running when the process was killed.\n\nLet me check if Unity actually completed successfully by looking more carefully at the log.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_nJhn4WWJ79qYndxxHXpN9521","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Content \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log\" -Tail 3","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":157,"output":407,"cacheRead":64384,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":64948,"cost":{"input":0.000021980000000000003,"output":0.00011396000000000001,"ca