{"type":"message","id":"a8adb656","parentId":"cee86fbc","timestamp":"2026-05-15T03:57:22.879Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The log doesn't have the typical success message, but the Unity process DID exit (I checked and it's gone). The log ended with a memory leak report and cleanup sequence. The absence of \"Exiting batchmode successfully now!\" and \"Exiting without the bug reporter\" could mean Unity exited abnormally.\n\nBut looking at the memory and cleanup signs, it seems like Unity went through its normal shutdown. The \"Cleanup mono\" and \"Server was shutdown\" messages indicate a normal shutdown sequence.\n\nThe issue might be that the bat process was killed (SIGKILL) - this could be because a new bat process was started from the same bat file while the previous one was still running. The first run's process might have been terminated when I started the second.\n\nActually, let me re-check. The first run (session `brisk-harbor`) ran the bat file. When I ran it again the second time (session `gentle-cove`), it started a new Unity process. But the first run's bat was still running... was it killed?\n\nLooking at the log, the first run wrote \"Exiting batchmode successfully now!\" at the end. The second run seems to have also gone through a similar shutdown but without that exact message.\n\nLet me look for more indicators of whether the pipeline actually succeeded. Let me search for \"Succeeded\" or check if any specific completion message exists.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_EgyelAIv77hIioyR4YF39921","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-Content \"E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon\\client\\cardv\\BuildPipeline_RunHotUpdate.log\" | Select-String -Pattern \"(Succeeded|succeeded|Canceled|Error|error|Exception|exception|Quit|quit|成功|失败)\" -Context 0,3","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":299,"output":413,